00:09:09,448 --> 00:09:12,709
that I'll follow on, was the idea of embodied condition.

167
00:09:14,095 --> 00:09:17,197
So it's typical to think that the mind affects the body.

168
00:09:17,197 --> 00:09:20,399
With embodied cognition, we allow ourselves to think

169
00:09:20,399 --> 00:09:24,821
that body movements affects our thinking.

170
00:09:24,821 --> 00:09:29,685
So for example, we can look at what happens with dancers.

171
00:09:30,804 --> 00:09:38,566
Like dancers, they learn choreographies to actually perform and make a performance.

172
00:09:38,566 --> 00:09:41,227
Learning a choreography takes a long time.

173
00:09:41,227 --> 00:09:44,668
It's quite complex in terms of model coordinations and everything.

174
00:09:44,668 --> 00:09:47,149
But they actually develop a trick.

175
00:09:47,149 --> 00:09:48,569
They have a technique called marking.

176
00:09:49,385 --> 00:09:52,526
that they used to learn choreographies much faster.

177
00:09:52,526 --> 00:09:54,988
So marking, it's not doing the choreography,

178
00:09:54,988 --> 00:09:57,289
it's kind of like sketching the choreography,

179
00:09:57,289 --> 00:10:00,391
like performing movements that kind of mimics

180
00:10:00,391 --> 00:10:01,612
the choreography without really putting

181
00:10:01,612 --> 00:10:03,533
the full energy into it.

182
00:10:03,533 --> 00:10:05,734
And that's like the way in which they learn

183
00:10:05,734 --> 00:10:07,355
choreographies like much faster.

184
00:10:07,355 --> 00:10:10,337
By moving their body, they actually influence

185
00:10:10,337 --> 00:10:11,377
their learning.

186
00:10:12,273 --> 00:10:15,974
We can actually see some research done by David Kirsch

187
00:10:15,974 --> 00:10:20,015
that's been looking at the way in which dancers

188
00:10:20,015 --> 00:10:21,156
are performing those markings

189
00:10:21,156 --> 00:10:22,656
and performing those movements

190
00:10:22,656 --> 00:10:25,077
for facilitating their learning.

191
00:10:25,077 --> 00:10:26,777
And that's exactly what I found out,

192
00:10:26,777 --> 00:10:29,218
that by mimicking the choreography,

193
00:10:29,218 --> 00:10:32,138
they were able to actually learn it much faster

194
00:10:32,138 --> 00:10:35,819
than doing the choreography full out, full force,

195
00:10:35,819 --> 00:10:37,880
or even just thinking about the choreography.

196
00:10:38,886 --> 00:10:42,210
Like what turned out that was helping them was like mimicking the movements,

197
00:10:42,210 --> 00:10:49,318
help them like to actually build a temporal model or a mental image of what the choreography

198
00:10:49,318 --> 00:10:54,864
would have been, like kind of like lay itself out in time and space and how to coordinate with others.

199
00:10:55,874 --> 00:11:00,198
So the idea here that we had was to leverage the same concept

200
00:11:00,198 --> 00:11:04,441
and think about what is the choreography that the player is

