251
00:13:44,473 --> 00:13:46,754
Because we need to understand that

252
00:13:46,754 --> 00:13:48,335
in order to make affordances for this.

253
00:13:49,093 --> 00:13:55,035
And that's the way in which we look, that's the way in which the human body looks inside

254
00:13:55,035 --> 00:13:56,235
like a man of reality.

255
00:13:56,235 --> 00:14:00,637
It's a VR monoculus with a head and two ears and not even eyes.

256
00:14:00,637 --> 00:14:04,178
They're actually kind of binocular holes, which are quite different.

257
00:14:04,736 --> 00:14:06,617
And we don't even have hands.

258
00:14:06,617 --> 00:14:08,958
We have some kind of punching gloves in there.

259
00:14:08,958 --> 00:14:10,599
And that's what makes a big difference

260
00:14:10,599 --> 00:14:13,040
in terms of affordances, because not having fingers

261
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:15,481
and having palms, it uses a lot of our ability

262
00:14:15,481 --> 00:14:17,042
to explore our surroundings.

263
00:14:17,042 --> 00:14:19,563
So the real question becomes, when

264
00:14:19,563 --> 00:14:21,224
you think about making anything that's

265
00:14:21,224 --> 00:14:23,925
like hand interactions in VR, how do you design

266
00:14:23,925 --> 00:14:25,025
an object for this creature?

267
00:14:26,347 --> 00:14:29,248
Because if you think about objects that we in real life,

268
00:14:29,248 --> 00:14:30,569
those are designed for our body,

269
00:14:30,569 --> 00:14:32,290
but now we have an embodiment which is different.

270
00:14:32,290 --> 00:14:34,271
How do you design an object for this creature?

271
00:14:34,271 --> 00:14:34,972
How do you find out?

272
00:14:34,972 --> 00:14:38,514
But the only way for us, or at least in our approach,

273
00:14:38,514 --> 00:14:41,616
the way that we actually move forward

274
00:14:41,616 --> 00:14:43,197
was surprise prototypes.

275
00:14:43,437 --> 00:14:46,038
You just have to fast prototypes as fast as you can,

276
00:14:46,038 --> 00:14:51,820
like make as many prototypes as you can to actually get a sense of what responds,

277
00:14:51,820 --> 00:14:53,281
what works for this VR homunculus.

278
00:14:53,281 --> 00:14:56,682
But also very important to use user testing as soon as possible,

279
00:14:56,682 --> 00:14:59,763
like prototypes alone, like that's only up to a point.

280
00:14:59,763 --> 00:15:02,965
You need to see other persons like jumping on board with those prototypes

281
00:15:02,965 --> 00:15:04,565
and see how far they go with that.

282
00:15:04,565 --> 00:15:05,926
It's important to prototype.

283
00:15:07,345 --> 00:15:12,130
I experience it is important to prototype as soon as possible,

284
00:15:12,130 --> 00:15:13,171
but not too early.

285
00:15:13,171 --> 00:15:15,974
Like, you know, bad ideas, it's like,

286
00:15:15,974 --> 00:15:16,935
better we adjust them.

287
00:15:16,935 --> 00:15:19,757
So our approach was like to kind of like user test internally

288
00:15:19,757 --> 00:15:21,639
and then like open up to other user testers.

289
00:15:21,639 --> 00:15:24,522
But like fast prototyping, it's been instrumental.

290
00:15:24,522 --> 00:15:28,005
It's been important for us also to think

291
00:15:28,005 --> 00:15:29,387
of these weapons like props.

292
00:15:31,163 --> 00:15:37,108
in the same way in which stage designers or people that work in theater think about props

293
00:15:37,108 --> 00:15:42,753
for actors, objects that are not really meant to work in certain ways but to suggest or

294
00:15:42,753 --> 00:15:44,655
elicit a certain way to act around them.

295
00:15:45,541 --> 00:15:49,443
And what also we found out was tremendously valuable.

296
00:15:49,443 --> 00:15:52,786
The prototypes became a communication tool

297
00:15:52,786 --> 00:15:53,986
inside the team.

298
00:15:53,986 --> 00:15:58,009
It was the best way to talk about VR interactions for us.

299
00:15:58,009 --> 00:16:00,871
Sometimes it's kind of complicated to talk about what

300
00:16:00,871 --> 00:16:02,172
will happen in VR.

301
00:16:02,172 --> 00:16:04,433
And you might write down, you might have

302
00:16:04,433 --> 00:16:05,854
pictures of animations.

303
00:16:05,854 --> 00:16:07,235
Sometimes nothing really works.

304
00:16:07,235 --> 00:16:11,077
You just have to have actual prototypes within the actual

305
00:16:11,077 --> 00:16:13,639
VR space where you see how things are unfolding.

306
00:16:15,008 --> 00:16:19,969
So let's look at the bow and let's look how the real bow translates into a bow for the

307
00:16:19,969 --> 00:16:20,049
B.R.

308
00:16:20,049 --> 00:16:20,470
Moleculus.

309
00:16:20,470 --> 00:16:22,330
How does the object change?

310
00:16:22,330 --> 00:16:27,852
So a real bow, it's an elegant, minimal design, but it's also quite sophisticated.

311
00:16:27,852 --> 00:16:32,734
There's a number of parts which are important for us to actually handle it properly.

312
00:16:32,734 --> 00:16:34,134
There is a grip.

313
00:16:34,334 --> 00:16:38,276
There is a harrow rest, which is where you place the harrow.

314
00:16:38,276 --> 00:16:40,197
More importantly, there is a serving,

315
00:16:40,197 --> 00:16:41,898
that area that you see over there.

316
00:16:41,898 --> 00:16:43,719
I don't know if you can see the pointer,

317
00:16:43,719 --> 00:16:47,021
but there's an area there where you can actually grab

318
00:16:47,021 --> 00:16:50,063
the string, pull it back.

319
00:16:50,063 --> 00:16:53,925
That part, which is actually quite thin in reality,

320
00:16:53,925 --> 00:16:57,227
in visual reality it became thick and really, really long,

321
00:16:57,227 --> 00:16:58,448
as long as the string.

322
00:16:58,448 --> 00:16:59,768
So it became kind of bulked up.

323
00:17:00,803 --> 00:17:05,986
Instead of having like a grip, we have to replace that with an attach point, something that gets attached to your hand.

324
00:17:05,986 --> 00:17:13,931
And something really important, because the VR Monocle doesn't have really eyes, they have like two binocular holes,

325
00:17:13,931 --> 00:17:21,616
we have to cut short and make the arrow appear as soon as you grab the knocking area.

326
00:17:22,456 --> 00:17:26,037
Because that was helping the person to have a straight line of sight.

327
00:17:26,037 --> 00:17:30,158
Because we wanted to actually have the person to actually achieve this idea of becoming better

328
00:17:30,158 --> 00:17:32,878
and becoming a master of shooting accurately.

329
00:17:32,878 --> 00:17:38,859
So that really helped to keep this straight line of sight.

330
00:17:38,859 --> 00:17:43,980
As much as it was helping, the other idea that we had to do

331
00:17:43,980 --> 00:17:46,321
was constraining certain worst orientations.

332
00:17:47,017 --> 00:17:52,298
like, like, there are ways of twisting your, like, your hands that, like, have been disabled

333
00:17:52,298 --> 00:17:58,379
where you actually control the bow, so that, like, the arrow get placed into line of sight,

334
00:17:58,379 --> 00:18:02,180
which is constant. So you constantly get reminded of what's, like, your line of sight. You can

335
00:18:02,180 --> 00:18:08,261
actually get into flow of using this bow quite fast and quite quickly. The final result was

336
00:18:08,261 --> 00:18:14,302
something that lends itself to be used in combat situations, also, like, when there's

337
00:18:14,302 --> 00:18:15,442
kind of, like, a frantic moment.

338
00:18:16,336 --> 00:18:20,098
And like, the player can actually shoot accurately,

339
00:18:20,098 --> 00:18:21,759
can get a sense of like becoming better,

340
00:18:21,759 --> 00:18:22,940
a bit more accurate.

341
00:18:22,940 --> 00:18:25,401
But it comes to do like stuff that you wouldn't do

342
00:18:25,401 --> 00:18:27,582
with a real bow, for example, shooting horizontally.

343
00:18:27,582 --> 00:18:29,803
That's something that like, it's connected,

344
00:18:29,803 --> 00:18:32,725
this idea of like enacting the use of an object

345
00:18:32,725 --> 00:18:34,326
so that you think like you are a hero.

346
00:18:35,405 --> 00:18:41,110
And that was pretty much what we did for the bow.

347
00:18:41,110 --> 00:18:45,013
It was important also to keep a consistent interaction,

348
00:18:45,013 --> 00:18:48,977
like design the object so that the player

349
00:18:48,977 --> 00:18:52,380
could keep a consistent rhythm of the interaction.

350
00:18:52,380 --> 00:18:55,423
And that's pretty much what we did for the bow in short.

351
00:18:56,679 --> 00:19:02,262
For the crossbow, it's a little bit more complicated because the crossbow is more recent as an object.

352
00:19:02,262 --> 00:19:10,627
There are many different variants, so we went into archives of museums and some other connections I have in Italy

353
00:19:10,627 --> 00:19:14,690
to actually study different variants, different crossbows and understand the various mechanics

354
00:19:14,690 --> 00:19:18,192
and what was the advantage of others compared to others.

355
00:19:19,012 --> 00:19:25,735
In general, the idea of the crossbow was to be able to load a bolt fast, so fast firing

356
00:19:25,735 --> 00:19:30,897
was the reason why they were invented.

357
00:19:30,897 --> 00:19:33,579
In my research I also find something...

358
00:19:35,288 --> 00:19:39,991
Quite interesting, I discovered that Leonardo da Vinci

359
00:19:39,991 --> 00:19:42,573
prototyped a crossbow, but just on paper.

360
00:19:42,573 --> 00:19:46,536
It was never realized, but it was like an automatic,

361
00:19:46,536 --> 00:19:48,577
like kind of like something you could load quickly.

362
00:19:48,577 --> 00:19:52,821
So there's this artisan in Italy who actually made it,

363
00:19:52,821 --> 00:19:54,722
this following the blueprint of Leonardo da Vinci.

364
00:19:55,222 --> 00:19:59,086
And it's a crossbow that is cut in half, so you can open it and it loads automatically.

365
00:19:59,086 --> 00:20:01,908
So the idea was really rapid firing.

366
00:20:01,908 --> 00:20:05,952
What we did for the crossbow was to think about how to fuse all these characteristics

367
00:20:05,952 --> 00:20:11,516
of different crossbows from different eras and try to fuse it into one object that we

368
00:20:11,516 --> 00:20:14,799
thought could be representative and different from the bow.

369
00:20:16,513 --> 00:20:17,715
in the way to use it.

370
00:20:17,715 --> 00:20:19,357
So we went through a number of prototypes,

371
00:20:19,357 --> 00:20:21,880
like modular prototypes that we build quite quickly

372
00:20:21,880 --> 00:20:24,263
out of gray boxing and like modular parts

373
00:20:24,263 --> 00:20:25,725
that you can interact with.

374
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:27,908
We started by having like an handle on top

375
00:20:27,908 --> 00:20:30,130
and then looking at people and how they were responding

376
00:20:30,130 --> 00:20:31,933
and how much they were getting into the flow.

377
00:20:31,933 --> 00:20:33,995
And then we moved the handles to the side.

378
00:20:34,651 --> 00:20:36,091
just to see what's the difference,

379
00:20:36,091 --> 00:20:37,572
if it was better for aiming or not.

380
00:20:37,572 --> 00:20:39,932
And then we even went as far as putting

381
00:20:39,932 --> 00:20:43,333
some kind of lever type of interaction here

382
00:20:43,333 --> 00:20:45,294
and kept looking at how people were moving

383
00:20:45,294 --> 00:20:46,354
and what we're doing.

384
00:20:46,354 --> 00:20:51,215
And the final version is this one over here,

385
00:20:51,215 --> 00:20:53,936
where you can grab the string and pull it backwards

386
00:20:53,936 --> 00:20:55,116
and it loads immediately.

387
00:20:55,116 --> 00:20:57,677
So if you become really good at doing this movement,

388
00:20:57,677 --> 00:21:00,157
you can actually shoot and reload it very fast.

389
00:21:00,157 --> 00:21:01,678
And then you can also grab it with two hands

390
00:21:01,678 --> 00:21:03,678
and do some more precision shooting.

391
00:21:04,768 --> 00:21:06,910
So that's what concerned looking at those objects

392
00:21:06,910 --> 00:21:08,131
in the virtual world.

393
00:21:08,131 --> 00:21:10,372
But it's interesting to look, as I said in the beginning,

394
00:21:10,372 --> 00:21:13,835
to look at how people responded in terms of movement.

395
00:21:13,835 --> 00:21:19,619
And this is actually the marking of the people mimicking

396
00:21:19,619 --> 00:21:23,081
like a certain character through the use of that object.

397
00:21:23,081 --> 00:21:26,103
So design the object so that people can move in certain ways

398
00:21:26,103 --> 00:21:27,024
when they were actually using it.

399
00:21:27,024 --> 00:21:31,507
And it's also important here to actually think about

400
00:21:31,507 --> 00:21:32,548
fatigue profiles.

401
00:21:33,200 --> 00:21:36,902
Like, since you design an object that gets used,

402
00:21:36,902 --> 00:21:38,904
that kind of like, you know, make people move

403
00:21:38,904 --> 00:21:40,345
in certain ways, you need to think about

404
00:21:40,345 --> 00:21:42,366
what kind of muscles get involved in there,

405
00:21:42,366 --> 00:21:44,047
and try to actually make fatigue profiles

406
00:21:44,047 --> 00:21:47,490
which are orthogonal between these two different objects.

407
00:21:47,490 --> 00:21:53,534
You can also see how the movements are not

408
00:21:53,534 --> 00:21:56,816
necessarily the same movements that we would do

409
00:21:56,816 --> 00:21:58,117
with the real objects.

410
00:21:58,117 --> 00:21:59,118
They're like sketched.

411
00:22:00,973 --> 00:22:06,959
But nevertheless, they are enough to actually build a mental model of what's happening inside the virtual world

412
00:22:06,959 --> 00:22:09,682
and what's happening when they are enacting into those objects.

413
00:22:10,500 --> 00:22:14,701
Another thing that we did that was very important was to parameterize the affordances.

414
00:22:14,701 --> 00:22:19,662
That was key for us because we didn't have much time to do user testing or formal user testing,

415
00:22:19,662 --> 00:22:24,523
so we had to go fast, try to iterate as fast as possible.

416
00:22:24,523 --> 00:22:29,664
So what we did was to organize the affordances into a number of parameters

417
00:22:29,664 --> 00:22:32,745
that we could actually tweak and change right after every user testing.

418
00:22:33,405 --> 00:22:46,470
So user testing was an occasion to observe people, but also to mold those values around what we found out was more or less comfortable, more or less easy to actually get working for the players when they were trying this.

419
00:22:47,115 --> 00:22:53,581
Also, once again, those parameters helped a lot as a communication tool, because it

420
00:22:53,581 --> 00:22:57,904
helped us to have a meeting where we were focused on certain ideas and certain concepts,

421
00:22:57,904 --> 00:23:04,129
so they really worked as a form of information architecture, provide us a vocabulary to talk

422
00:23:04,129 --> 00:23:10,435
about what we saw during these user experiences, during user testing.

423
00:23:12,303 --> 00:23:18,933
Something that was also very important that sometimes get overlooked was active feedback.

424
00:23:18,933 --> 00:23:22,858
They put a lot of effort into trying to actually get it right.

425
00:23:22,858 --> 00:23:29,067
Why it's important? Because active feedback is a way to highlight a rhythmic pattern of the interaction.

426
00:23:29,748 --> 00:23:32,711
Also, VR tends to be very loaded on the vision.

427
00:23:32,711 --> 00:23:36,055
It tends to be visually very loaded.

428
00:23:36,055 --> 00:23:39,339
So to actually provide feedbacks in a subtle way

429
00:23:39,339 --> 00:23:41,721
through vibrations is actually a good thing.

430
00:23:41,721 --> 00:23:45,646
It reduces the current load on the person.

431
00:23:47,267 --> 00:23:49,308
But for example, let's look at the bow,

432
00:23:49,308 --> 00:23:52,710
at the act of shooting the bow,

433
00:23:52,710 --> 00:23:57,954
and how the active feedback comes into play

434
00:23:57,954 --> 00:23:59,595
to actually define or reinforces

435
00:23:59,595 --> 00:24:02,497
the idea of a tempo of the interaction.

436
00:24:02,497 --> 00:24:07,019
Reinforcing the idea of a certain rhythm,

437
00:24:07,019 --> 00:24:09,741
and getting into a rhythmic pattern as using this object.

438
00:24:09,741 --> 00:24:14,844
That's achieved by providing an active feedback

439
00:24:14,844 --> 00:24:16,265
in key moment of the interaction.

440
00:24:17,886 --> 00:24:20,488
like when the player touches the string,

441
00:24:20,488 --> 00:24:21,868
first you get a first impulse,

442
00:24:21,868 --> 00:24:23,829
then you get a longer one when you grab the strings,

443
00:24:23,829 --> 00:24:25,270
then you get a progressive one

444
00:24:25,270 --> 00:24:26,831
when the string gets pushed backward,

445
00:24:26,831 --> 00:24:28,511
and then you get a shake.

446
00:24:28,511 --> 00:24:30,292
So all of those active feedback

447
00:24:30,292 --> 00:24:32,473
are there to actually mark a tempo in time,

448
00:24:32,473 --> 00:24:34,975
that in turn gets the person

449
00:24:34,975 --> 00:24:37,356
into a repetitive flow of movements

450
00:24:37,356 --> 00:24:40,657
and getting into the repetition of those movements

451
00:24:40,657 --> 00:24:42,538
like in a form of a static of interaction.

452
00:24:44,725 --> 00:24:49,750
Something we didn't realize early on when we started working on the two weapons,

453
00:24:49,750 --> 00:24:55,977
especially because the crossbow, as an idea, came further down into the game,

454
00:24:55,977 --> 00:25:00,502
was that the two, like these two weapons, like in games when you add a new weapon,

455
00:25:00,502 --> 00:25:03,665
it's like adding more to what you already have.

456
00:25:05,387 --> 00:25:10,250
But here it was really about adding an extra object.

457
00:25:10,250 --> 00:25:17,316
And also demanding the person to actually re-learn a new set of movements.

458
00:25:17,316 --> 00:25:20,078
Because the handling of the two objects is different.

459
00:25:20,078 --> 00:25:24,822
The bow is something that, let's say you hold with your left hand and you operate it with your right hand.

460
00:25:24,822 --> 00:25:26,603
The crossbow is the other way around.

461
00:25:26,603 --> 00:25:28,905
You hold it with your right hand and you operate it with your left hand.

462
00:25:31,767 --> 00:25:36,229
So, like, when you tend to use one object, you build up the muscle memory of that object,

463
00:25:36,229 --> 00:25:39,831
and when you switch to another weapon, the muscle memory doesn't work anymore, you have

464
00:25:39,831 --> 00:25:41,552
to relearn it.

465
00:25:41,552 --> 00:25:46,514
And that's, you know, it's a bit different, like, from games, where, like, ultimately

466
00:25:46,514 --> 00:25:50,556
all the weapons really, like, you know, it boils down to pressing buttons, like, at least

467
00:25:50,556 --> 00:25:52,176
like a sensory motor level.

468
00:25:52,176 --> 00:25:54,257
But here it's different.

469
00:25:54,670 --> 00:25:58,512
So having new weapons required new conditioning and effort.

470
00:25:58,512 --> 00:26:01,373
Something has to be considered that we did not consider first,

471
00:26:01,373 --> 00:26:03,294
but then we kind of like crashed onto it

472
00:26:03,294 --> 00:26:06,175
and we had to work around it.

473
00:26:06,175 --> 00:26:09,277
But the good news was that we found a way

474
00:26:09,277 --> 00:26:10,977
to interpret these differences.

475
00:26:10,977 --> 00:26:13,258
And instead of looking at them as two different weapons,

476
00:26:13,258 --> 00:26:15,199
we started looking at them as two different classes,

477
00:26:15,199 --> 00:26:17,240
two different ways of playing the game.

478
00:26:17,240 --> 00:26:19,341
So they were like two different gameplay styles.

479
00:26:20,935 --> 00:26:23,036
And when we actually started looking in that way,

480
00:26:23,036 --> 00:26:26,618
everything became like, in a way, like more productive

481
00:26:26,618 --> 00:26:30,080
in a sense that we could see how we could imagine

482
00:26:30,080 --> 00:26:33,002
two different communities of players forming out there,

483
00:26:33,002 --> 00:26:33,962
one that prefers the bow,

484
00:26:33,962 --> 00:26:35,823
another one prefers the crossbow,

485
00:26:35,823 --> 00:26:38,545
and start kind of like competing each other out

486
00:26:38,545 --> 00:26:42,007
in performances around the idea of like designing,

487
00:26:42,007 --> 00:26:45,228
like designing objects like in a different way.

488
00:26:47,165 --> 00:26:52,129
So here's where we had to go through a very intense user

489
00:26:52,129 --> 00:26:54,611
testing session that was done remotely.

490
00:26:54,611 --> 00:26:56,613
Because at that point, the game was already in early

491
00:26:56,613 --> 00:27:01,216
access, so we got a few very dedicated players on board.

492
00:27:01,216 --> 00:27:03,498
They really wanted to test the new additions, one of which

493
00:27:03,498 --> 00:27:04,779
was the new weapon.

494
00:27:04,779 --> 00:27:07,982
And at the beginning, they hated it, because they were

495
00:27:07,982 --> 00:27:09,103
super good at playing the bow.

496
00:27:09,103 --> 00:27:11,084
And then suddenly, they have to relearn the things from

497
00:27:11,084 --> 00:27:13,306
scratch, and they didn't like it.

498
00:27:13,606 --> 00:27:18,271
But there wasn't really a way to be able to operate the crossbow the same way in which

499
00:27:18,271 --> 00:27:18,812
you operate the bow.

500
00:27:18,812 --> 00:27:20,674
It's like they're two different objects.

501
00:27:20,674 --> 00:27:23,016
You can't really manipulate them in the same way.

502
00:27:23,016 --> 00:27:26,300
So by doing something I've never done before, like some...

503
00:27:28,138 --> 00:27:31,221
like remote user testing through Slack,

504
00:27:31,221 --> 00:27:33,885
we were able to actually like work really well.

505
00:27:33,885 --> 00:27:36,748
They were like incredibly passionate about the game,

506
00:27:36,748 --> 00:27:38,610
so they start like commenting and talking to each other

507
00:27:38,610 --> 00:27:40,612
how it works and what not, and that was like

508
00:27:40,612 --> 00:27:43,776
very good for me to keep a track of all those conversations.

509
00:27:44,436 --> 00:27:48,737
And also what was really important was asking them to send me

510
00:27:48,737 --> 00:27:51,678
video recording of their play sessions because it was

511
00:27:51,678 --> 00:27:56,099
really hard to understand, or it was really hard to read through what they were actually experiencing.

512
00:27:56,099 --> 00:28:00,760
It was important to see what was happening really in the game.

513
00:28:00,760 --> 00:28:03,141
So that was something I didn't expect to work out.

514
00:28:03,141 --> 00:28:07,462
It could have worked out, but it worked out pretty well.

515
00:28:07,462 --> 00:28:09,103
So just to conclude...

516
00:28:10,699 --> 00:28:12,460
forget any rules about like practical,

517
00:28:12,460 --> 00:28:17,602
practical like trigs or practical like rule of thumbs here.

518
00:28:17,602 --> 00:28:18,502
Technology is changing.

519
00:28:18,502 --> 00:28:20,643
As the technology is changing,

520
00:28:20,643 --> 00:28:23,024
the VR monoculus will look more and more like a person.

521
00:28:23,024 --> 00:28:25,045
So the affordances will be different.

522
00:28:25,686 --> 00:28:30,870
Like what's really a takeaway is not about how to do things in the details,

523
00:28:30,870 --> 00:28:37,075
but to keep looking at people and keep looking at how people move.

524
00:28:37,075 --> 00:28:40,417
So not only focus on what's happening on the screen and what's happening in the virtual world,

525
00:28:40,417 --> 00:28:43,140
but look what people do, because that's where part of the fun is coming.

526
00:28:43,140 --> 00:28:49,425
Part of the fun is coming from making an experience which is kinesthetic and fun in a kinesthetic way.

527
00:28:50,386 --> 00:28:52,368
So in a sense, like practice dancing, in a sense,

528
00:28:52,368 --> 00:28:54,851
like reconnect to your body, like rediscover

529
00:28:54,851 --> 00:28:56,853
what's fun to do with your body, in a sense,

530
00:28:56,853 --> 00:28:59,036
because that allows you to connect

531
00:28:59,036 --> 00:29:01,779
to this idea of making beautiful experiences

532
00:29:01,779 --> 00:29:02,900
through body movement.

533
00:29:02,900 --> 00:29:08,667
And that concludes my talk, and I'm open for questions.

534
00:29:08,667 --> 00:29:08,887
Thanks.

535
00:29:25,207 --> 00:29:26,428
Yeah.

536
00:29:26,428 --> 00:29:29,290
I have a lot of trouble using haptics in VR,

537
00:29:29,290 --> 00:29:33,452
and especially when doing the up and down modulation

538
00:29:33,452 --> 00:29:35,293
that you showed in a graph.

539
00:29:35,293 --> 00:29:38,575
Can you share your technique with making that happen?

540
00:29:38,575 --> 00:29:38,956
Technique.

541
00:29:39,672 --> 00:29:44,717
Yes, so the graph I showed is a very crude representation,

542
00:29:44,717 --> 00:29:49,802
because haptic is like frequencies and amplifications.

543
00:29:49,802 --> 00:29:54,627
But what I did was basically having a similar approach

544
00:29:54,627 --> 00:29:56,508
to motion design.

545
00:29:56,508 --> 00:30:00,813
So I made a way to actually modulate the haptics

546
00:30:00,813 --> 00:30:02,414
through a couple of parameters.

547
00:30:03,195 --> 00:30:08,097
And then I tweaked them until I was getting a response that I thought was actually good.

548
00:30:08,097 --> 00:30:11,338
And then I also created different categories.

549
00:30:11,338 --> 00:30:16,140
There's something that I call the haptic click, that mimics a click,

550
00:30:16,140 --> 00:30:22,263
or it's kind of like a soft, rhythmic feedback.

551
00:30:22,263 --> 00:30:25,084
And then another one which is thicker and longer.

552
00:30:25,084 --> 00:30:28,865
I don't really know a better way to describe it. It's a bit like describing sounds.

553
00:30:29,879 --> 00:30:36,426
like taking it longer. And then like I remember something that worked really well. It was

554
00:30:36,426 --> 00:30:41,371
like the shake on the bow. Like it's an up to feed, but it just like shakes like this.

555
00:30:41,371 --> 00:30:44,855
Like it kind of like gives you the idea of like.

556
00:30:45,160 --> 00:30:48,162
like energy that gets released into the object.

557
00:30:48,162 --> 00:30:51,644
But the main concept really that I wanted to show

558
00:30:51,644 --> 00:30:54,726
was really try to place it into key moments

559
00:30:54,726 --> 00:30:55,446
of the interaction.

560
00:30:55,446 --> 00:30:57,467
Like try to imagine the interaction

561
00:30:57,467 --> 00:30:59,408
almost like a dramaturgy.

562
00:30:59,408 --> 00:31:01,770
And try to imagine what could be the point

563
00:31:01,770 --> 00:31:03,711
where you want to make an emphasis in the tempo.

564
00:31:05,369 --> 00:31:09,412
And that's at least what I found out was the most effective way to do it.

565
00:31:09,412 --> 00:31:11,433
And then of course the user testing.

566
00:31:11,433 --> 00:31:15,896
Sometimes I overdid it, I put too much of it and it was getting confusing.

567
00:31:15,896 --> 00:31:21,841
So as a little term, like in music, it's better to just be conservative and not add too much

568
00:31:21,841 --> 00:31:22,301
on it.

569
00:31:22,301 --> 00:31:25,443
Thank you very much.

