00:34:14,188 --> 00:34:15,349
Thanks.

625
00:34:15,349 --> 00:34:19,232
I have a follow up question about the Haptecs.

626
00:34:19,232 --> 00:34:22,374
So did you design them as audio waveforms

627
00:34:22,374 --> 00:34:25,296
that are parameterized so that they change procedurally?

628
00:34:25,296 --> 00:34:27,197
Or did you do something else for that?

629
00:34:27,197 --> 00:34:29,419
No, I wanted to design them as sound waves.

630
00:34:29,419 --> 00:34:32,041
There was no time for that.

631
00:34:32,041 --> 00:34:35,823
So I designed them as animation curves.

632
00:34:36,783 --> 00:34:39,625
that they were just like bound between zero and one.

633
00:34:39,625 --> 00:34:41,506
So they were like normalized,

634
00:34:41,506 --> 00:34:43,388
but then you could add parameters to them

635
00:34:43,388 --> 00:34:46,230
to kind of change them in terms of like length, amplitude.

636
00:34:46,230 --> 00:34:48,171
So those are the kind of parameters that I was changing.

637
00:34:48,171 --> 00:34:51,233
So probably there was like a better way

638
00:34:51,233 --> 00:34:54,876
to make it like more refined in terms of active feedback.

639
00:34:54,876 --> 00:34:57,217
I'm pretty sure like if you talk to someone

640
00:34:57,217 --> 00:34:59,018
which is very expert of active feedback,

641
00:34:59,018 --> 00:35:00,579
can tell you like a much better way to do it.

642
00:35:01,680 --> 00:35:05,461
For me, from the point of view of the interaction design and the general UX,

643
00:35:05,461 --> 00:35:08,362
it was important to nail that concept of rhythm.

644
00:35:08,362 --> 00:35:10,462
Like, when do we want to have them?

645
00:35:10,462 --> 00:35:13,043
At what point of the interaction do we want to have them?

646
00:35:13,043 --> 00:35:15,984
And it's like, what types of active feedback do we want to have?

647
00:35:15,984 --> 00:35:17,964
How long it is, how intense it is?

648
00:35:17,964 --> 00:35:20,225
As I said before, to classify them into things.

649
00:35:20,225 --> 00:35:24,866
But I was really keen to actually try the sound waves

650
00:35:24,866 --> 00:35:27,007
and see what would come out of it.

651
00:35:27,449 --> 00:35:35,093
I don't even know if the controllers that we have at the moment are actually responding

652
00:35:35,093 --> 00:35:37,855
very deeply to this kind of sine wave optics.

